eas, like ensuring a binder bean auto-configures with Embedded Kafka, and verifying health indicators. I also want to be careful about avoiding multiple Spring contexts and managing the embedded broker life cycle appropriately.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Configuring Spring Cloud Stream**\\n\\nI need to set the broker properties in the SpringApplication settings, derived from `broker.getBrokersAsString()`, and ensure unique topics are created. It looks like I might need dependencies for JUnit, possibly AssertJ. I’ll be using SpringApplicationBuilder, making sure it's set to `WebApplicationType.NONE`, and include a configuration class with `@SpringBootApplication` to trigger autoconfiguration.\\n\\nSince my test package is outside of `org.springframework`, I think a nested static configuration could work. I’m defining functional beans, including a consumer and a simple function for producer and consumer scenarios. For output through StreamBridge, I’ll set properties accordingly, including bindings and destinations.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Configuring Kafka and Spring Cloud Function**\\n\\nI'm considering how to set up StreamBridge for autoconfiguration and realize it's only effective within the Spring Cloud Function context. I think I'll need to use KafkaTestUtils to handle the consuming aspect. There might also be a need to inspect the API. I wonder what specific details I should understand about the consumerProps signature to ensure everything works smoothly. Each step feels crucial to getting the configuration just right!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_g7DmPKCEdoXqkuuXSx3ZBNGd|fc_0c7ca2edfcc00c63016a4031ca5d308195aa6c686b1cbda49a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "cd /tmp/scsk && jar tf spring-kafka-test-4.0.2-sources.jar | grep KafkaTestUtils && jar xf spring-kafka-test-4.0.2-sources.jar org/springframework/kafka/test/utils/KafkaTestUtils.java && grep -n \"consumerProps\\|getSingleRecord\" org/springframework/k