[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m exploring a missing health indicator bean. Maybe the ConditionalOnEnabledHealthIndicator is using management.health.defaults, or the binder context doesn’t recognize the parent. I wonder if the KafkaBinderHealthIndicatorConfiguration was imported correctly in the child context; if it’s not, the app context may lack the indicator. I could modify the build.gradle if necessary. However, if we can't establish a health indicator, we should consider if using the Actuator health endpoint might help. But it mustn’t become a brittle solution.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Reconsidering health check dependencies**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m thinking about the best way to handle the health check in the integration test. One option is to remove the health check entirely, along with its imports and possibly the Spring Boot health dependencies. But the KafkaBinderHealthIndicator needs consideration; it seems the dependency isn't referenced in the test even though it's needed for compilation. I wonder if I can disable binders health auto-configuration to avoid unnecessary dependencies, especially since earlier exceptions showed issues when enabling health checks.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Examining configuration issues**
[thinking] 
[thinking] If I remove the health check, there’s a chance the runtime will still fail due to a missing EndpointAutoConfiguration. The initial failure was linked to setting management.health.binders.enabled to true, which may have pulled in BindersHealthIndicatorAutoConfiguration. If I disable it, I wonder if conditional introspection could still cause issues. It seems that this auto-configuration is always imported by spring-cloud-stream and relies on the EndpointAutoConfiguration annotation, which means I need the actuator-autoconfigure dependency unless I decide to exclude the auto-configuration.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Checking dependencies in Spring Boot**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm considering the intricacies of a Spring Boot project related to dependencies like spring-boot-health and whether to keep actuator-autoconfigure. It seems the Kafka binder compiles dependencies from spring-boot-starter-actuator in the POM. I wonder if Gradle is optional in this context. However, I remember we added actuator-autoconfigure, which is key for Spring Stream auto-configuration. It leads me to think that boot-health might transitively come from actuator-autoconfigure. I'll need to check the POM to confirm if there's a dependency there.
